content.problemStatement:
- So far, we've only attached a listener to one button. But what if you have a calculator with twenty buttons (0-9, +, -, =, etc.)?
You could write twenty separate listeners:
```js
document.querySelector('#btn-7').addEventListener('click', runSeven);
document.querySelector('#btn-plus').addEventListener('click', runPlus);
// ...and so on for 18 more lines...
```
This is slow, repetitive, and messy!

**The Solution: The Event Object**
- When any event (like a 'click') occurs, the browser automatically creates an Event Object. This object is a temporary container of all the information related to that event: when it happened, where it happened on the screen, and, most importantly, which specific element triggered it.
- The Event Object is automatically passed as the first argument to your callback function. You usually name this argument simply `event` (or just `e`).
```js
button.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
    // The 'event' object is available inside this function!
});
```
**The Star Property: `event.target`**
- The most useful part of the Event Object is the `.target` property.

| Property | What it gives you | Why it matters |
|----------|-------------------|----------------|
| `event.target` | A reference to the exact HTML element that was clicked. | It allows you to use one listener for hundreds of elements, making your code clean and scalable. |

**Syntax**
- You can instantly get the properties of the clicked element using `event.target`:
```js
// The callback receives the event object
function logClick(event) {

    // Use .target to access the clicked element's text content
    const clickedElement = event.target;

    // Log the text of the button that was pressed
    console.log(`You clicked the button with text: ${clickedElement.textContent}`); 

    // You can also change the style of the clicked element!
    clickedElement.style.backgroundColor = 'yellow';
}

// Attach ONE listener to a container that holds many buttons
container.addEventListener('click', logClick);
```

